We proceed by integration by parts. Let

\begin{align*}
u = e^{2x} \quad & \quad v = -\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} \\
du = 2e^{2x}dx \quad & \quad dv = \sin(2x)dx \end{align*}

and so the integral becomes

\begin{align*}
\int  e^{2x}\sin(2x)\,dx &= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2}  + \int e^{2x}\cos(2x) \, dx\end{align*}

We use parts again. Let

\begin{align*}
u = e^{2x} \quad & \quad v = \frac{\sin(2x)}{2} \\
du = 2e^{2x}dx \quad & \quad dv = \cos(2x)dx \end{align*}

Then, we have

\begin{align*}
\int  e^{2x}\sin(2x)\,dx &= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} + \int e^{2x}\cos(2x) \, dx\\
&= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} + \left( \frac{e^{2x}\sin(2x)}{2} - \int e^{2x}\sin(2x) \, dx \right)\\
&= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} + \frac{e^{2x}\sin(2x)}{2} - \int e^{2x}\sin(2x) \, dx\end{align*}

This last integral on the right is the same as the integral on the left
(up to a constant). Hence, we have

\begin{align*}
\int  e^{2x}\sin(2x)\, dx +  \int e^{2x}\sin(2x) \, dx  &= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} + \frac{e^{2x}\sin(2x)}{2} +C \\
2\int e^{2x}\sin(2x) \, dx  &= -e^{2x}\frac{\cos(2x)}{2} + \frac{e^{2x}\sin(2x)}{2} +C \\
\int e^{2x}\sin(2x) \, dx  &= -\frac{e^{2x}\cos(2x)}{4} + \frac{e^{2x}\sin(2x)}{4} +D \end{align*}

where $D = 2C$. This completes the question.
